EXPOSE and Port Binding
Objectives
Understand how to document and expose ports in container images
Learn to map container ports to host ports
Test network connectivity between containers and host systems
Troubleshoot common port binding issues
Prerequisites
Podman installed (version 3.0+ recommended)
Basic familiarity with Linux command line
Text editor (vim/nano/gedit)
Network connectivity
Curl or telnet for testing
Lab Setup
Verify Podman installation:

podman --version
Expected output: podman version 3.x.x

Create a working directory:

mkdir portbinding-lab && cd portbinding-lab
Task 1: Using EXPOSE in Containerfile
Subtask 1.1: Create a Simple Web Application
Create a Python web app file:

cat > app.py <<EOF
from flask import Flask
app = Flask(__name__)

@app.route('/')
def hello():
    return "Hello from the exposed container port!\n"

if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run(host='0.0.0.0', port=8080)
EOF
Create requirements.txt:

echo "flask" > requirements.txt
Subtask 1.2: Create Containerfile with EXPOSE
Create a Containerfile:
cat > Containerfile <<EOF
FROM python:3.9-slim
WORKDIR /app
COPY . .
RUN pip install -r requirements.txt
EXPOSE 8080
CMD ["python", "app.py"]
EOF
Key Concept: The EXPOSE instruction documents which ports the container listens on but doesn't actually publish them.

Task 2: Run Container with Port Mappings
Subtask 2.1: Build the Image
podman build -t exposed-app .
Subtask 2.2: Run with Port Mapping
Map container port 8080 to host port 8080:

podman run -d -p 8080:8080 --name webapp exposed-app
Verify the container is running:

podman ps
Expected output should show the running container with port mapping.

Troubleshooting Tip: If you get a port conflict, try a different host port (e.g., -p 8081:8080).

Task 3: Test Connectivity from Host
Subtask 3.1: Verify Port Mapping
Check port binding on host:

ss -tulnp | grep 8080
Test the application:

curl http://localhost:8080
Expected output: Hello from the exposed container port!

Subtask 3.2: Test with Different Port Mapping
Stop previous container:

podman stop webapp
Run with different host port:

podman run -d -p 9090:8080 --name webapp2 exposed-app
Test the new port:

curl http://localhost:9090
Task 4: Troubleshoot Port Conflicts
Subtask 4.1: Simulate Port Conflict
Try to bind to an occupied port:
podman run -d -p 8080:8080 --name webapp3 exposed-app
Expected: Error about port already in use
Subtask 4.2: Resolve Conflict
Find the conflicting process:

sudo lsof -i :8080
Solutions:

Stop the conflicting service
Choose a different host port
Use -P to let Podman choose a port:
podman run -d -P --name webapp4 exposed-app
podman port webapp4
Conclusion
In this lab, you learned:

How to document container ports using EXPOSE in Containerfiles
The difference between exposing and publishing ports
Multiple methods for port mapping with Podman
Techniques for troubleshooting port conflicts
Final Verification:

List all containers:

podman ps -a
Clean up:

podman stop -a && podman rm -a
